---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const post = {
 title: 'Minimum Order Quantity for Embroidery and Screen Printing: What\'s Realistic',
 description:
 'Most embroidery and screen-print shops set 12-24 pieces as the practical minimum. Here\'s why MOQs exist, what drives them, and how to get small-batch (1-12 piece) work done when you genuinely need it.',
 category: 'Operational',
 readTime: '7 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/service-embroidery.jpg',
 slug: 'minimum-order-quantity-embroidery-screen-printing',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'What\'s the minimum order for custom embroidered shirts?', a: 'Most commercial embroidery shops set 12-24 pieces as the practical minimum. Below that, per-piece pricing climbs because digitizing fees and setup are amortized over fewer shirts. Below 12 pieces, embroidery may not be cost-effective compared to alternatives like heat-transfer vinyl or DTF (direct-to-film).' },
 { q: 'What\'s the minimum order for screen printing?', a: 'Most commercial screen printing shops set 24 pieces as the practical floor. Setup costs — screen burning, ink mixing, registration — don\'t amortize well below 24. For 12-24 piece runs, expect higher per-piece pricing. Below 12, screen printing rarely makes financial sense vs. heat transfer or DTF.' },
 { q: 'Can I get 6 custom shirts made?', a: 'Yes, but not via traditional embroidery or screen printing economics. For runs under 12 pieces, the alternatives are: heat-transfer vinyl (HTV), direct-to-film (DTF) printing, sublimation (for polyester), or premium small-batch embroidery with a small-order surcharge. The output looks similar; the cost structure is just different.' },
 { q: 'Why do embroidery shops have minimums?', a: 'Setup costs. Digitizing the logo (one-time fee, $30-80 per logo), thread color matching, hooping, and machine prep all happen regardless of order quantity. At 24+ pieces, the setup is amortized to a few cents per shirt. At 6 pieces, the setup adds significant per-piece cost.' },
 { q: 'How do I get cheaper per-piece pricing?', a: 'Order more pieces in a single run. The biggest cost lever in custom apparel is quantity. A 24-piece order is typically 30-50% more expensive per piece than a 144-piece order of the same shirt and decoration. For ongoing programs, batching reorders monthly or quarterly captures the volume discount.' },
 { q: 'Can I combine multiple orders to hit a minimum?', a: 'Sometimes. If you have multiple decorations on the same blank, the shop might combine the artwork into a single press run and split the finished pieces between your orders. Talk to the shop — most are willing to combine when it makes sense.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the difference between minimum order and minimum run?', a: 'Minimum order is the smallest total piece count the shop will accept (typically 12-24). Minimum run is the smallest piece count of a single SKU/color/decoration combination — sometimes shops have a 6-piece minimum per color or per garment style within a larger order.' },
]

const schema = {
 '@context': 'https://schema.org',
 '@graph': [
 { '@type': 'Article', headline: post.title, description: post.description, image: `https://bighornthreads.com${post.image}`, datePublished: post.isoDate, dateModified: post.isoDate, author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Bighorn Threads', url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/' }, publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Bighorn Threads', logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/images/logos/bighorn-logo-color.png' } }, mainEntityOfPage: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` },
 { '@type': 'BreadcrumbList', itemListElement: [{ '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/' }, { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Blog', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/blog/' }, { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: post.title, item: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` }] },
 { '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })) },
 ],
}
---

<BaseLayout title={post.title} description={post.description} canonical={`https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/`} ogImage={post.image} type="article" publishedDate={post.isoDate}>
 <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
 <article class="bg-navy-950">
 <header class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-navy-800">
 <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-navy-950 via-navy-900 to-gray-900"></div>
 <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 pt-20 pb-12 sm:px-6 sm:pt-24 lg:px-8">
 <nav class="mb-6 font-mono text-xs text-gray-400" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/" class="hover:text-gold-400">Home</a><span class="px-2">/</span><a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-gold-400">Blog</a></nav>
 <span class="mb-3 inline-block text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">{post.category}</span>
 <h1 class="mb-6 font-heading text-3xl font-bold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">{post.title}</h1>
 <p class="mb-8 text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-300">Why MOQs exist, what drives them, how to get small-batch work done when you genuinely need it, and how to optimize larger orders for better per-piece pricing.</p>
 <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-4 gap-y-2 border-t border-navy-800 pt-6 font-mono text-sm text-gray-400"><span class="text-gold-500">Bighorn Threads Team</span><span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span><span>{post.readTime}</span><span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span><time datetime={post.isoDate}>{post.date}</time></div>
 </div>
 </header>
 <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 pt-10 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><img src={post.image} alt="Stack of custom embroidered work shirts in production at a Las Vegas commercial decoration shop" width="1200" height="675" loading="eager" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-navy-800 object-cover shadow-2xl" /></div>
 <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

 <aside class="mb-10 rounded-2xl border border-gold-500/30 bg-navy-900/60 p-7">
 <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">Quick Answer</p>
 <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-white sm:text-xl">Most commercial embroidery shops set 12-24 pieces as the minimum order; most screen print shops set 24 as the floor. Below those quantities, setup costs (digitizing, screen burning, ink mixing) don't amortize well and per-piece pricing climbs sharply. For very small runs (1-12), heat-transfer vinyl or DTF (direct-to-film) printing offers different economics that work for small batches.</p>
 </aside>

 <h2 id="why-moqs" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Why Minimum Orders Exist</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Custom apparel decoration has fixed setup costs that happen once per run regardless of quantity:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
 <li><strong>Digitizing</strong> (embroidery) — one-time fee per logo, $30-80, converts your logo into a stitch file the machine can read.</li>
 <li><strong>Screen burning</strong> (screen printing) — one-time per color per run; the screen has to be coated with emulsion, exposed, washed out, and registered.</li>
 <li><strong>Ink mixing</strong> (screen printing) — pantone color matching takes time and ink that isn't recoverable.</li>
 <li><strong>Hooping / press setup</strong> — the machine has to be threaded, tensioned, and registered for each run.</li>
 <li><strong>Color matching + proofing</strong> — making sure the output matches expectations.</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">At 24 pieces, that setup is amortized to maybe $1-2 per shirt. At 6 pieces, it's $4-8 per shirt — making the per-piece total often higher than buying retail.</p>

 <h2 id="alternatives" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Alternatives for Small Batches (1-12 pieces)</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">For runs under the embroidery/screen-print MOQ, four alternatives have different economics:</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Heat-Transfer Vinyl (HTV)</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">A vinyl decal is laser-cut from your logo, then heat-pressed onto the garment. Per-piece cost is low because there's no setup beyond the cut file. Output is a solid-color flat decal that works for simple logos and team names. Limitations: gradients and fine detail don't translate, and the decal can lift over time after many washes.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Direct-to-Film (DTF)</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">A newer technology that prints your design onto a film, then heat-transfers it to the garment. Handles full-color gradients and detail that HTV can't. Per-piece cost is low because there's minimal setup. Durability is improving but generally less than properly cured plastisol screen prints.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Sublimation (polyester only)</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Heat-transfers dye into polyester fibers permanently. Excellent durability and color reproduction, but only works on white or light-colored polyester. Common for athletic wear and event tees.</p>

 <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Small-batch embroidery with surcharge</h3>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Some shops will run 4-12 piece embroidery orders with a small-order surcharge that covers the setup. Per-piece price is higher but you get the premium look of stitched embroidery on a polo or work shirt. Worth asking for if HTV/DTF doesn't fit the use case.</p>

 <h2 id="optimizing-larger" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Optimizing Larger Orders for Better Per-Piece Pricing</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Three patterns that capture volume discount without overshooting demand:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
 <li><strong>Batch monthly or quarterly.</strong> Instead of ordering 12 pieces for new hires every month, batch into a 36-piece quarterly order. Per-piece pricing drops without overstocking.</li>
 <li><strong>Standardize SKUs.</strong> If you can run the same Carhartt K87 in three colors (24 black, 12 navy, 12 charcoal) the entire 48-piece batch shares setup costs.</li>
 <li><strong>Use a <a href="/company-stores/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">company store</a>.</strong> Aggregate employee orders into a single weekly or monthly press run. Bigger run, lower per-piece cost, no inventory overhead.</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="other-factors" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Other Cost Factors Beyond Quantity</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Even within a single quantity tier, three factors move the per-piece price meaningfully:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
 <li><strong>Stitch count or color count.</strong> A simple bold logo embroiders cheaper than a detailed multi-color one. A single-color screen print costs much less than a 6-color print. See <a href="/blog/how-much-to-embroider-a-shirt/" class="text-gold-400 underline decoration-gold-500/30 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-500">how much to embroider a shirt</a> for the full pricing breakdown.</li>
 <li><strong>Garment cost.</strong> A Gildan 2000 vs. a Bulwark FR shirt is a 10x cost spread on the blank.</li>
 <li><strong>Decoration placements.</strong> A single left-chest logo costs less than a chest + sleeve + back combination because each placement is a separate press operation.</li>
 </ul>

 <div class="mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-gold-500/40 bg-gold-500/5 p-7 sm:p-9">
 <h2 class="mb-3 font-heading text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-white">Need to figure out the right order size?</h2>
 <p class="mb-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Bighorn Threads quotes embroidery and screen printing for Vegas contractors, trades, and crews of all sizes. We'll tell you straight when small-batch HTV or DTF makes more sense than traditional embroidery, and we'll help you size larger orders for the volume discount.</p>
 <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex min-h-[48px] items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-gold-500 px-7 py-3 text-base font-bold text-navy-950 transition-all hover:bg-gold-400">Get a Quote →</a>
 </div>
 </div>
 </article>
</BaseLayout>
